properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight. Snow currently over the area is expected to transition to snow squalls this evening into tonight. At this point in time, the heavy squalls are likely to impact areas just north of London and Woodstock. A Snow Squall Warning is likely by this evening as these squalls develop. Any snow squalls that form will last into Saturday morning before shifting northward during the day. Through this same period of time, winds are forecast to gust up to 60 km/h resulting in local blowing snow in the snow squalls, particularly over exposed areas. Hazards: Locally 5 to 15 cm of snow by Saturday evening. Quickly accumulating snow at times. Poor visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow. Impacts: Hazardous travel tonight into Saturday. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A potent winter storm will impact northern Kivalliq beginning overnight Saturday toward Sunday morning. This storm will bring significant winds, with gusts near 90 km/h possible. This system will also bring near 10 cm of snow. These winds combined with the falling snow will lead to significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow, possibly creating blizzard conditions. Conditions will gradually improve late on Monday. Please stay alert to updated bulletins as warnings will likely be issued as the system approaches. Refer to local forecasts for more information on when the inclement weather is expected and specific snowfall amounts. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

Heavy rain is expected for southwestern Nova Scotia and parts of Cumberland County. As a result, rainfall warnings are in effect for those areas. Later on Saturday, rain is likely to switch to snow for some areas as the temperatures drops. Locally snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm are possible, especially over higher terrain. Conditions will improve Saturday night. In addition, higher than normal water levels are expected from Lunenburg east to Sheet Harbour near 5 am AST on Saturday. Wave heights of up to 6 metres are expected along the Atlantic coast beginning early Saturday and persisting most of the day. Coastal flooding is not expected at this time. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls tonight into early Saturday morning. A snow squall has developed over Lake Ontario and will impact the area through tonight. The snow squall will be particularly intense overnight and into early Saturday morning. The snow squall is expected to shift southward into New York State on Saturday morning. Wind gusts of 60 to 70 km/h will result in local blowing snow over exposed areas. Hazards: Locally 5 to 15 cm of snow by Saturday morning. Quickly accumulating snow of up to 5 cm per hour at times. Poor visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow. Impacts: Hazardous travel, particularly along portions of Highway 401. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
